<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1508542-what-is-the-point-of-triffids-the-book-is">What is the point of Triffids? The book is pretty much a clean end-of-the-world scenario and Triffids seem a little bit tacked on. Is there a history about why author added something as unrealistic as them in the book? Was it to claim it was nature&#39;s revenge for humanity&#39;s treatment of it, or maybe pressure from editor to add monsters to make it more horror-like?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1508542'><a id="like_count_community_question_1508542" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/1508542?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">1 like</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F530965.The_Day_of_the_Triffids">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1508542-what-is-the-point-of-triffids-the-book-is">2 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1508542-what-is-the-point-of-triffids-the-book-is">Add your answer</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/86159158-spock-s-cat"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1535788260i/86159158._UY100_CR18,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/86159158-spock-s-cat">Spock&#39;s Cat</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    I'm not sure about why they were added but I did want to point out that they are definitely not natural and, therefore, not "nature's revenge". If any<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    I'm not sure about why they were added but I did want to point out that they are definitely not natural and, therefore, not "nature's revenge". If anything, it's more a case of humanity getting its comeuppance. <br /><br />And, in fact, now I think about it, that may actually partially answer your question; both the triffids and the 'comets' are meant to indicate humanity's technology and, indeed, its hubris, gone spectacularly wrong. The moral, therefore, is that we brought about the end of the world ourselves chiefly because we were too greedy (farming the triffids for financial gain) and too sure of our own superiority (only our sight gave us an advantage over the triffids, not the brains we're so proud of - this is actually discussed early on in the narrative).<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
</div>
